bug.short_desc: Cache ODA extension manifest objects for better performance

long_desc.thetext:
The ODA framework provides an utility class (org.eclipse.datatools.connectivity.oda.util.ManifestExplorer) to encapsulate the access of an ODA extension's manifest information. as the PPT emitter doesn't follow the engine extension point strictly (it use engine internal structure), so i think we need postphone this SCR to 2.2.
The PPT emitter uses PDF layout engine to calculate the content layout while we assume that all third party emitter should use HTML layout engine instead.
The PDF layout engine use an internal interface IArea to represent the layout information, that interface is not as stable as IContent (which is used by the HTML layout engine).
To resolve this problem completely, we need add a new property into the emitter extension point which declare which layout result this emitter need. There should be three kind of layout result:
1. No layout result (it contains no layout result, even the pagination). 2. Limit layout result (birt will layout the content into pages depends on the page-break property just like HTML, the content size is not considered). 3. Full layout result, birt layout the content into pages depends on the content size and page size just like the PDF.
The default layout engine will be 2 (HTML).
We also need consider formalize the IArea object to represent the layout result for PDF.
we need add a property to control the pagination of the emitter.

bug.short_desc: no way to add 2 different php executables with the same name

long_desc.thetext:
As it stands now, if 2 php runtime on different paths both have the same name, there's no way to add both of them into the Installed PHPs preferences list. The name of a runtime should really be distinguished from the name of it's executables.
The Add PHP dialog should automatically search for a directory entry that matches a list of possible php executable names, run it to determine it's version and then append the php runtime version to the php executable name to generate a default php runtime name.
A simpler but acceptable solution will be to simply askes to users to input a php executable name instead of searching.

Eden has sent me an email and asked for an explaination of this bug, so here it is:
Suppose there are 2 php executables: /opt/local/bin/php (php5) /usr/bin/php (php4)
Since they are both named "php", I can't add both of them to the installed PHP list. The reason for this is that I can't alter the name of the runtime executable and PHP IDE has made a false assumption that each PHP interpreter has a unique name. There are 3 ways to solve this bug:
1. Distinguish the interpreter by path names 2. Distinguish the interpreter by versions 3. Ask the user to input different name for each interpreter.

Thanks so much for the clarification. The field you are talking about is just a label for the php executable, it doesn't have to be the actual name of the executable! You can give it whichever name you want. The field description is indeed misleading. It will be modified in the next version.

bug.short_desc: Strange compile error for final static strings if value == null

long_desc.thetext: JLS 3 8.1.3 states that: - inner classes are non static classes enclosed into another class; - inner classes can define static members iff these are compile-time constant fields. JLS 3 15.28 in turn excludes null from compile-time String constants. Hence the behavior is conformant to the specification.
Added regression tests ConstantTest#test019 and test020.

I personally find it VERY odd and awkward that ... private final static String EMPTY = null; ...
should be any different from: ... private final static String EMPTY; static { EMPTY = null; } ...
IMHO *both* cases should be handled as explicit initialization and even generate code! BTW: I am sure I have seen debuggers actually single stepping through such assignments, so obviously at least some compilers do consider also the first case as a code producing "statement", not just a declaration.
Only ... private final static String EMPTY; ...
(i.e. without any assignment) should be considered as NOT initialized (an no initialization code behind it).
But who am I to blame you if the specs say something different... Stupid specs! :-(

So for example, “FooBah” becomes “fooBah” “Z” becomes “z” “URL” becomes “URL” We provide a method Introspector.decapitalize which implements this conversion rule." (http://java.sun.com/products/javabeans/docs/spec.html)
The conclusion is: For a field called eMail, we should call the getter 'geteMail'. If we would call it getEMail, Java Beans would conclude that this is a constant name and assume the property is 'EMail'.
Getter and setter names are created using NamingConvention.suggestGetter/SetterName. Moving to jdt.core.

There are 2 options of creating a new internal browser: using a new window every time or opening the URL in the same window, using the same browser ID. In the class "DefaultBrowserSupport" there is a function called "getExistingWebBrowser". The function checks if the given ID exists in the hash "browserIdMap". If it doesn't it creates a new browser and it enters the ID in the hash. If the id exists it should open the URL in the same window, but it doesn't happen. The reason is the following: Every time a URL is sent to the browser, it is added to the browser history in the function "setURL" (there is a call to 'addToHistory')in class "BrowserViewer". In 'addToHistory' there is a call to WebBrowserPreference.setInternalWebBrowserHistory. This call triggers a call to "update" in the observer attached to DefaultBrowserSupport. (in the constructor). In the update the hash "browserIdMap" is cleared!!!! It means that it is impossible to use the "Existing browser" feature, since the browserIdMap is cleared on every call. There is a TODO remark in the 'update' function saying: "// TODO I am not sure what we should do here // The preferences have changed so maybe we should // close the opened browsers in addition to clearing // the table "
browserIdMap.clear(); is clearly NOT what needs to be done here, at least not in every case.

bug.short_desc: Module name clash not detected

long_desc.thetext:
Got me for a few minutes this one.
If you have two projects open in your workspace that define the same module name in .component, there is no warning.
The effect of this is that if you've checked out two different tags/branches of a module into the same workspace, and have both open, WTP has two to choose from, and quite silently deploys one of them to the server (in my case the wrong one.. which is how I noticed).
Now.. I think this falls into the realm of J2EE Module Dependencies, which I understand is supposed to determine what gets deployed to the server.
There seems to be a few problems with this: 1) It's clearly not getting used in 1.5 release, as anything I tick gets cleared when I close and reopen the project. 2) The duplicate module name is not seen in that dialog, but instead the old module name (which happens to be the same as the project name)
Desired behaviour would probably be that deploy (TC5.5 in my case) fails as it detects that it has more than one module of the required name to choose from.

Assigning to Larry since it sounds like a server (Tomcat) specific issue to check for duplicates. (other servers might have the same problem, but they'd have to specifically check for whatever they don't support) If this ends up involving module dependancies it should go to the J2EE team.

Confirmed in WTP 2.0 M6 that multiple modules with the same deploy-name can be added to a Tomcat server. This creates a problem because that name is used for the directory name where the module is published. I'll try to address this in the first WTP 2.0 release candidate.
To be decided is what to do exactly. The new "Serve modules without publishing" option would allow the multiple modules to be served since only the root-context needs to differ for this use case. I could allow the modules to be added to the server and only complain if it were published without the "Server modules without publishing" option. However, this could complicate removing a project from a server and lead to some confusion seeing multiple modules with the same name in the Servers view and Add and Remove Projects dialog.

After investigating, it turns out the problem goes deeper than Tomcat. My apologies for not seeing this sooner.
For WTP to function correctly with respect to module handling, the current code requires that the project name and the deploy-name match. This means that a couple of simple usage scenarios aren't fully supported. These are copying and pasting a Dynamic Web Project (since the deploy-name isn't currently changed to match the new project name) and checking a project out of a source repository into a project whose name doesn't match the deploy-name. Two basic breakages I've seen is being unable to associate a resource in a project to the corresponding module (for Run on Server) and determining which project belongs to a module when multiple projects have the same deploy-name.
I will enter an enhancement request that WTP not require that the project name match the deploy-name. I expect it will be after WTP 2.0 before this can be addressed. I'll include additional detail in that report. Once that is addressed, I can look into what Tomcat can do when projects with the same deploy-name are added to the server. It may be possible to deploy them as long as the context-roots are different. For now I need to remove the 2.0RC0 target.

Sorry to hear it's deeper, but not surprising. Perhaps the "checking out multiple branches/instances to same workspace" use case needs addressing globally.
I say that, as I've found various errors when working on fixes to two branches of code simultaneously. Eclipse often opens the wrong source file in response to clicking on an exception URL.
I'll keep an eye out for those use cases and report them. Until now, I've just accepted them as me being an awkward user :)

bug.short_desc: WSDL Editor, Outline View -> Imports -> Open Import does not work for file or http based locations

long_desc.thetext:
The WSDL Editor's Outline view has an Imports group with items that each have an "Open Import" action in their context menu. However, it appears that the action only works for locations that use the "platform:/resource" scheme. If the action is invoked on a import location URI that uses the file:/ or http:/ URI schemes (i.e. a WSDL file outside the workbench) then the action does nothing.
This seems to be a fairly big limitation of the WSDL editor - I can't find any way to open an editor for a WSDL file that is not located in the workbench.

We've been looking at trying to create a patch for this. One of the biggest problems we are encountering is that the editor code casts to IFileEditorInput, and appears to rely heavily on the IFile retrieved from this. This is very limiting, ideally editors should work with IEditorInput and be tolerant of unmodifiable resources. Yes - it is an editor, but editors are viewers too!

Created an attachment (id=49628) Workaround for this problem that uses links
This is an attempt to workaround the IFileEditorInput constraint. It creates a linked IFile for non-workspace (specifically http and file) URLs, and so can pass an IFileEditorInput to the WSDL editor. It works for file URLs. I think it will work for http URLs too - when the problems with the StructuredSourceEditor assuming that IFile.getLocation() always returns a non-null value are resolved (see bug 154471) - but right now there is a NPE thrown for http URLs, although after the error dialog is closed the editor recovers gracefully and opens just the design view (nice). Its not ideal, as e.g. it leaves the files links in the project - although that might actually be seen as useful for a user. The real solution for this is that all WTP editors properly support IEditorInput, so we can edit non-workspace resources. But please consider this patch for the shortterm.

Sorry, my original description is misleading. It's not that tab itself that is missing the border, but the table that lists the extensions, to the left of the column of buttons inside the extensions tab.

Based on my long years of experience, this typically happens when the code lacks 'toolking.paintBordersFor(container);' line of code. On some platforms, form toolkit uses native border because it is flat to begin with. In this case, the call above will be a no-op. However, on platforms where 3D border is used, toolkit will create trees and tables without the SWT.BORDER style and paint its own 2D border (as in the Extension Points page).
This particular problem happened to us during the Forms tutorial on this year's EclipseCon :-).
And of course, it is 'toolkit' and not 'toolking' (Tool King? :-).
It is possible that you are not having enough margin around because the border painters needs some breathing space (2pix) around the widget.

OK, that explains it. According to my own eclipse.org article, you should do the following:
myControl.setData(FormToolkit.KEY_DRAW_BORDER, FormToolkit.TREE_BORDER);
i.e. where 'myControl' is the widget for which you want border painted.

bug.short_desc: [Viewers] Deprecate ViewerSorter, getSorter() and setSorter()

long_desc.thetext:
The API added in 3.2 to allow JFace viewers to compare strings using arbitrary Comparators, not just Java Collators, is very badly designed. A kludge had to be inserted somewhere between StructuredViewer and the initialization of the ViewerSorter with a Java collator, so ViewerSorter was copied and pasted as ViewerComparator and most of the members were pushed up. I think it would be much better to allow a ViewerSorter to have an arbitrary comparator, defaulting to the one from the JFace Policy (which in Eclipse is an ICU collator because they're better than Java ones). My reasoning:
- ViewerComparator is a bad name as it does not suggest how that class differs from ViewerSorter (i.e., arbitrary comparator vs. Java collator). It would be much less confusing to have only one class.
- All existing clients that call StructuredViewer.getSorter() will break on a viewer whose comparator was configured using the new API (i.e. ViewerComparator), even if the ViewerComparator actually contains a Java collator. If instead getSorter() returned a ViewerSorter whose getCollator() returns null, those clients would only break if they try to use the collator. Furthermore, it might be possible to implement getCollator() so that if the comparator happens to be an ICU collator, it is wrapped in a proxy that looks like a Java collator. Then clients would only break if they ask for a Java collator from a ViewerSorter that isn't using either a Java or an ICU collator, which probably will never happen.
- A lot of existing code says "viewer.setSorter(new ViewerSorter());". Under the current API, that will result in a sort using the default Java collator. It would be much easier to make "new ViewerSorter()" return a sorter that uses the default ICU collator than to change all calls to "viewer.setSorter(new ViewerSorter())" into "viewer.setComparator(new ViewerComparator())".
Furthermore, there are only two references to ViewerComparator outside JFace itself, one of which was introduced only yesterday in response to bug 153463. Thus, I don't think anyone will complain if we back out the API from 3.2 and do it a better way.
If you like this proposal, I would be happy to implement it myself and post the patch.
see comment 8 in bug 153463 for design reasoning.

If it's essential that ViewerSorter.getCollator() never return null, it could use the same kludge as the following early adopters of ICU: org.eclipse.jdt.internal.ui.search .JavaSearchResultPage.DecoratorIgnoringViewerSorter org.eclipse.jdt.ui.JavaElementSorter org.eclipse.search.internal.ui.text.FileSearchPage Namely, return java.text.Collator.getInstance() even though that isn't actually the comparator being used.

(In reply to comment #0) > Furthermore, there are only two references to ViewerComparator outside JFace > itself, one of which was introduced only yesterday in response to bug 153463. > Thus, I don't think anyone will complain if we back out the API from 3.2 and do > it a better way.
This is not an option. We cannot break binary API compatibility.

Boris of course has made the strongest point but to add:
We considered that option in 3.2 but it didn't make sense for a series of reasons
1) Many sorters make no use of a Collator so having one that had no dependency was quite useful
2) Forcing the use of a Collator when it was never used was just bad style - especially if someone made the mistake of thinking the Collator for the sorter was used in the sorting and made assumptions about it
3) Creation of Collators can be slow in both icu and java.util. If an RCP app wants to avoid the potential of creating on on startup for instance having no reference to collators is a good way to do it.

(In reply to comment #0) > - All existing clients that call StructuredViewer.getSorter() will break on a > viewer whose comparator was configured using the new API (i.e. > ViewerComparator), even if the ViewerComparator actually contains a Java > collator.
Yes. Clients can only move to the new story if they don't pass the viewer instance to existing code which is not aware of getComparator(). Where is this a problem?

I don't understand #1-3, but I see that nothing major can be done given an absolute requirement of binary compatibility. Nonetheless, StructuredViewer.getSorter() should probably be deprecated, and perhaps StructuredViewer.setSorter() and ViewerSorter should also be deprecated. In fact, the javadoc for ViewerSorter says "It is recommended to use ViewerComparator instead"; that could be turned into a real deprecation.
Is there anything that prevents us from deprecating in 3.3?
I think we decided not to deprecate in 3.2 because the changes were done post-API freeze (with approval, of course). So I can't think of a reason why they should not be deprecated.
Waiting for some action on bug 154884 before I deprecate.

I think TreePathViewerSorter should also be deprecated. A class named TreePathViewerComparator should be introduced that subclasses ViewerComparator. Also, Martin suggested that the ViewerSorter class not be deprecated as it will introduce alot of warnings that people likely aren't going to fix. Instead we deprecated the getCollator method of ViewerSorter. See bug 158118 for more details.
I think this bug should be marked WONTFIX in light of bug 158118 comment 6.

bug.short_desc: DeltaProcessor does not set project references if first build is a project build

long_desc.thetext:
When creating a new workspace with several projects, the DeltaProcessor will fail to set the project references correctly (and as a result, the build order will be wrong) if a project build runs before autobuild builds the entire workspace.
The delta attached to the PRE_BUILD event for the very first project build is relative to the entire workspace and contains all the information needed to set the project references for all projects. The problem is caused by the check on the first line of DeltaProcessor.resourceChanged():
public void resourceChanged(IResourceChangeEvent event) { if (event.getSource() instanceof IWorkspace) {
I talked to Jerome and he believes this was a leftover from the very early days.
Removing the check fixes the problem trying to build our workspace from scratch.

bug.short_desc: [ICU] Platform should adopt using ICU Collator using new APIs

long_desc.thetext:

bug.short_desc: SWTLaunchConfiguration should respect getEnvironment()

long_desc.thetext:
SWTLaunchConfiguration extends AbstractJavaLaunchConfigurationDelegate and thus should use getEnvironment(ILaunchConfiguration) method in SWTLaunchConfiguration.launch().
Instead, it uses:
String envp[] = DebugPlugin.getDefault().getLaunchManager().getEnvironment(configuration);
This doesn't allow subclassing of SWTLaunchConfiguration for e.g. a profiler plugin. The intention of AbstractJavaLaunchConfigurationDelegate was to allow such subclassing.

Just to be clear:
SWTLaunchConfiguration is internal. It is not API and is not meant to be subclassed by clients.
There is an ongoing attempt in JDT to retire the SWT launcher by finding alternatives (bug 122527). So I don't see us promoting the SWT launcher to API status any time soon.

Whenether SWTLaunchConfiguration is internal or not, it might use the new API. This API was especially introduced in Eclipse 3.2. The problem is that YourKit Java Profiler (http://www.yourkit.com) already allows to profile SWT applications, because our users demand this feature. To implement this feature we need to copy-paste entire SWTLaunchConfiguration and tweak it a little.
Please take a look at bug #77566, bug #88642 and bug #116844. All these bugs are about the same thing.
Best regards, Vladimir Kondratyev YourKit, LLC http://www.yourkit.com "Don't get lost in data, get information!"

The point that it is an internal component doesn't reflect in UI in any way. And user must not care about that.

bug.short_desc: Allow to mark tasks from web queries as completed

long_desc.thetext: Allow to mark tasks from web queries as completed
Done. Note that I had to move WebTask into mylar.internal.tasks.core.
Created an attachment (id=48538) mylar/context/zip

Mik, this is kind of ugly hack... :-)
Note that there are list of related issues:
-- priority for web tasks can't be changed -- make resolved/unresolved does not appear in the popup menu for task editor -- task editor does not show the Task Info panel (where you can change priority) like it does for local tasks
So, maybe we should have some flags/capabilities on ITask, such as locallyCompletable() and locallyPrioritized(). Then maybe make query hits to be adaptable to ITask...

It is quite ugly and requires explicit testing for instanceof WebTask, which is clearly wrong. Yes, the priority stuff is very similar, and setting the description is also related. What I don't want to move towards is having a capability for every attribute that can be set locally. The model is: 1) for repository tasks info comes from the server 2) for personal tasks info comes from the local workspace 3) personal planning and notes are metadata that work for all tasks
For instances where we can not get the server data (e.g. the limited generic web connector) the best solution seems to be to shadow this data locally. My feeling is that this makes sense for completion because it's simply necessary, but I feel that makes less sense for priorities. What do you suggest?

I agree about the points where info comes from. However it is unclear what info could come from server, since all servers have different capabilities.
So, I think it does make sense to have priorities locally when not supported by server.
Description is trickier because if we change it locally it will be flipped back after the next synchronization with server, unless there would be special handling for this (if it is not there already).
We can look trough other connectors in the list and see if they all support priorities.

So it sounds like we can make a tentative rule: if the connector does not support retrieving some of the task information from the server, we allow that to be 'shadowed' locally for the user's convenience.
For the web connector this would mean: * completion and priorities can be set locally * descriptions can not be set locally (since they are retrieved on synch)
All other current connectors have the ability to get priorities from the server. If you agree with this scheme I can update the API and UI accordingly.

I think we have no choice there. However descriptions would get trickier. Should we allow to edit descriptions if user dragged task out of query? Probably not...
But when same issue added as "existing repository task" we need to allow to edit description (similar to web-linked tasks) and would be strange limitation to not allow to edit it afterwards.
So I wonder if we should have separate local and remote descriptions to handle this tisutation for web tasks.
> All other current connectors have the ability to get priorities from the > server.
How about connectors we have in the list? For example email/news connector probably won't have priorities.
> If you agree with this scheme I can update the API and UI accordingly.
I think that makes sense.
